                  <p>The commissioner was ˀabunä ˁAynä Krǝstos mentioned in the supplication formulas (see fol. <locus target="#125"/>
                     <locus from="136rb" to=""/>va, where also his relatives and disciples are recalled; see also the Miracles). The manuscript was originally in possession of the monastery on the island of Mǝṣraḥa on Lake Ṭana (see Pankhurst <locus target="#1973"/>:<locus target="#15"/>), where ˀabunä ˁAynä Krǝstos could have been the abbot. </p>
                  <p>The manuscript was possibly one of those taken to Mäqdäla by King Tewodros II (r. <locus from="1856" to="68"/>) even though it lacks the typical possession note referring to the church Mäqdäla Mädḫane ˁAläm. The troops of the Napier Expedition captured Mäqdäla on <locus target="#13"/>April <locus target="#1868"/>. Does the note on fol. <locus target="#1a"/>indicate that G. Lents got the book in his possession <locus target="#13"/>April <locus target="#1868"/>? (on the fate of the books from Mäqdäla Mädḫane ˁAläm, see the recent Ancel – Nosnitsin <locus target="#2014"/>).</p>
                  <!--The commissioner was ˀabunä ˁAynä Krǝstos mentioned in the supplication formulas (see fol. 125, 136rb-va, where also his relatives and disciples are recalled; see also the Miracles). The manuscript was originally in possession of the monastery on the island of Mǝṣraḥa on Lake Ṭana (see Pankhurst 1973:15), where ˀabunä ˁAynä Krǝstos could have been the abbot.  The manuscript was possibly one of those taken to Mäqdäla by King Tewodros II (r. 1856-68) even though it lacks the typical possession note referring to the church Mäqdäla Mädḫane ˁAläm. The troops of the Napier Expedition captured Mäqdäla on 13 April 1868. Does the note on fol. 1a indicate that G. Lents got the book in his possession 13 April 1868? (on the fate of the books from Mäqdäla Mädḫane ˁAläm, see the recent Ancel – Nosnitsin 2014).-->
               </person>
            </listPerson>
